A black box in the car?
U.S. road planners are looking for a source of money to repair the decaying highway system, and believe they have found the solution in a small black box that fits into every car’s dashboard.
The devices that record every mile driven and report the information to the authorities are at the heart of a controversial attempt by Washington and the federal planning agencies to revise the outdated system to finance U.S. roads.
The usually rather boring area of road planning has suddenly sparked an intense debate with colorful alliances.
Libertarians have allied themselves with environmental groups and are in favour of the government using the small boxes to record the mileage traveled – and possibly also where they were driven – and then using the information to calculate tax breaks.
The tea party is outraged.
The American Civil Rights Association (ACLU) is also deeply concerned and expresses a number of privacy concerns.
But while one cannot agree on a move in Congress, several states are no longer waiting.
They are currently looking at how to switch over the next ten years to a system where drivers pay per mile driven.
Thousands of drivers have already tested the drivers, some of them equipped with GPS monitoring.
This is really a must for our country.
“There’s nothing we’re just likely to use,” said Hasan Ikhrata, managing director of the Southern California Assn. of Governments, which plans to record the mileage of all California drivers in the state from 2025.
The way we pay these taxes is going to change.
The technology for that is there.
The initiative comes at a time when the Highway Trust Fund, which is funded from the taxes that Americans pay at the zapfsäule, is pledging.
In America, however, not as much is being tanked as before.
Cars consume less gasoline.
The state mineral oil tax of 18.4 cents per gallon (less than 4 eurocents per liter) has not risen in 20 years.
Politicians do not dare to raise the tax by a single cent at high spray prices.
“The gasoline tax is simply not future-proof,” said Lee Munnich, an expert on traffic law at the University of Minnesota.
Its state has recently equipped 500 cars with pens to test a mile-based payment system.
“This is the most meaningful alternative in the long term,” he said.
Bureaucrats call it a mile-based user fee.
It is not surprising that the idea is appealing to urban liberals, because, for example, the tax could be used to influence driving behaviour in such a way as to reduce pollution and climate-damaging exhaust gases.
California’s planners rely on the system to devise strategies to achieve the state’s ambitious, legally enshrined climate change goals.
But Republican Bill Shuster of Pennsylvania, chairman of the House Transportation Committee, has also stated that he sees it as the most common long-term alternative.
The free marketers of the Reason Foundation are also motivated by the idea of allowing drivers to pay on a backward track.
“This is not a tax that disappears in a black hole,” explains Adrian Moore, Vice President of Policy at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The movement is also supported by two former U.S. transport ministers who, in a 2011 report, had urged Congress to move toward mileage-based billing.
The U.S. Senate approved last year a $90 million expensive pilot project that would have included 10,000 cars.
But the majority in the House of Representatives prevented the push and thus responded to the concerns of deputies from rural areas, who represent people who often have to lay many miles on their way to work or to the city in everyday life.
Nevertheless, several states and major cities are moving in this direction on their own initiative.
The most dedicated is Oregon, which currently hires 5,000 drivers for the country’s largest experiment.
These drivers will soon pay the mileage fees to the state instead of the mineral oil tax.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is considering one as well.
Illinois is testing it to a limited extent with trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transport ministries of 17 states on the East Coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is currently investigating how the change could be introduced.
The concept is not a universal hit.
In Nevada, where 50 volunteers were recently equipped with the equipment, motorists were skeptical that the government could track any of their movements.
“Concerning Big Brother and things like that was a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, head of strategy and earnings management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
People didn't want it.
When the test arrived, the ACLU of Nevada warned on its website: “It would be relatively easy to turn the drive recorders into adult surveillance devices.”
There is no need to build a gigantic, bulky technological infrastructure that would inevitably be used to capture data on the daily movements of individuals.
Nevada is one of a number of states that are now looking for affordable technology that allows the state to track the mileage, but not exactly when and where.
So, according to Khan, the public would also be more relaxed.
Hunting for this technology has led some authorities to a small startup company called True Mileage in California.
The company did not initially act to help states with taxing motorists.
Rather, it was its goal to take a foothold in an emerging market for car insurance, where drivers are expected to pay based on the miles driven.
However, the devices tested by her are also interesting for road planners, because they do not work with GPS and only provide limited information that is regularly uploaded via modem.
“People are more willing to participate if their speed and locations aren’t recorded,” said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
In some of these public pilot programs, big mistakes have been made.
There are significantly cheaper and less intrusive ways to implement this.
In Oregon, the planners are experimenting with giving drivers a range of choices.
You can opt for a device with or without GPS.
Or they don’t choose a device at all and instead pay a flat-rate fee based on the average mileage driven by all the residents of the state.
Other agencies hope to be able to sell the concept of a distrustful public by equipping the devices with more functions than with fewer.
In New York City, traffic officials want to develop a taxation device that also allows parking fees to be paid, insurance to be paid only for driven miles, and speed data from other vehicles to be collected in real time, allowing drivers to avoid traffic jams.
“Drivers would be motivated to participate because of the added value of the benefits the system offers,” the city said in a planning document.
However, some traffic planners wonder if the whole talk about paying per mile isn’t just a huge distraction.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission for the San Francisco Bay Area, officials said Congress could solve the problem of the failed Highway Trust Fund simply by raising fuel taxes.
An additional one-off fee or an annual fee could be imposed on drivers with hybrid vehicles or other vehicles that consume little gasoline, so that they also pay a fair share.
“There’s no reason for an operation if an aspirin is enough,” explains Randy Rentschler, the Commission’s Head of Legislation and Public Affairs.
