Esa decides on large space missions: missions for billions
Remote planets, gravitational waves or black holes - European space agency experts now have to agree on two major projects they want to launch in the coming years.
There were 30 proposals to choose from, five are still in the race.
Faraway worlds.
Astronomers have already found more than 1,000 planets on other stars.
Whether there is life on at least some of it, no one knows.
The choice is difficult: Should you look for gravitational waves?
Or would you rather explore the origin of the cosmos?
Or are they going to Earth-like planets and perhaps discover extraterrestrial life?
These are the questions posed by the European Space Agency (ESA).
For their “Cosmic Vision” program, they are looking for ideas for two large space projects that are designed to drive research decisively.
The budget for such "L-Missions" is about one billion euros each.
The launch is expected to be 2028 and 2034.
At the beginning of September, the elite of European space research met in Paris to discuss proposals for such missions.
30 ideas were debated, five of which have now come to the narrower election.
Numerous committees are considering the proposals, and the researchers are looking into them.
In the coming days, a final decision will be taken by the Scientific Programme Committee.
In total, Esa has selected four major questions to which the missions of the Cosmic Vision programme, initiated in 2007, should be answered.
What are the conditions for the formation of planets and life?
The exact processes in the formation of stars from large gas clouds - and thus also the formation of planets that surround these stars - are still in the literal darkness.
A large infrared telescope in space could penetrate this darkness.
And if a star has a planet, under what circumstances can life arise there?
To address this question, the 2017 Space Telescope "Cheops" is to launch, with which 500 already known planetary systems in our immediate vicinity will be studied in more detail.
However, the possibilities are limited, Cheops is a small mission with a budget of 150 million euros.
With larger instruments, astronomers could image Earth-like planets and even analyze the composition of their atmospheres and thus look for "biomarkers": gases that are considered to be an indication of biological activity.
How does the solar system work?
In the end, this question should also give an indication of what conditions exist for the creation of life.
An important role is played by the magnetic activity of a star and the interaction of its magnetic field as well as the particle radiation from it with the planetary system.
In our solar system, these processes can be investigated exemplaryly.
With the "Solar Orbiter", the Esa has already approved an M-Class mission (there the budget is about half a billion euros) for this question.
The probe is set to launch in 2017 and closely observe the surface and activity of the sun.
Jupiter and its moons are also of great interest to researchers.
They want to find out what role the giant planet played in the development of the solar system.
The Esa is the first of three L missions in the Cosmic Vision program.
The probe "Juice" (Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer) is expected to begin its journey in 2022.
Eight years later, she reaches Jupiter and is to study the atmosphere of the planet as well as the icy moons Europa, Kallisto and Ganymed.
What are the basic physical laws of the universe?
The universe offers many possibilities to study matter under extreme conditions and thus to examine whether the laws of nature we know are still valid there.
Perhaps there are also deviations that could point physicists the way to a new theory, under whose roof all known laws of nature can be united.
How did the universe come into being and where does it come from?
13.7 billion years ago, our cosmos was created by the Urknall.
In addition to the matter that is common to us, of the stars, planets and living beings as we are, there is Dark Matter, whose gravitational pull of galaxies and galaxy clusters together, and Dark Energy, through whose action the expansion of the universe accelerates.
So far, the researchers do not know which physical laws were valid in the first fractions of the primordial nucleus, nor what dark matter and dark energy are made of.
With Euclid, the Esa has already approved an M mission, which is scheduled to launch in 2020.
With a special telescope, the probe is intended to investigate the distribution of matter in the universe for the first time across the entire sky, allowing conclusions on the nature of dark matter and dark energy.
Who could make the race
Of the 30 proposals, only two will remain at the end of the selection process.
In the opinion of many experts, "E-Lisa" has the best chance of obtaining a permit as an L-Mission, a sophisticated concept for detecting gravitational waves.
Physicists understand changes in the structure of spacetime that Albert Einstein predicted almost 100 years ago.
They have not been proven to this day.
Elisa could do that, hopefully the scientists behind the project.
The mission includes a detector consisting of two or three probes, which is stationed in the space.
Unlike plants on Earth, it could also detect gravitational waves that originated during the Urknall, thus providing new insights into the origin of the cosmos.
Four more proposals are still competing for the second L-mission: a large X-ray telescope called "Athena", which will explore black holes, among other things, "Icy Planets", another mission to the outer planets of the solar system, "Prism", a mission to probe the outer planets of the solar system, "Under-planet" and "Exoplanet", a mission to measure the cosmic background.
Proposals for the return of samples from Mars, for the exploration of the moon, Venus and asteroids, as well as for solar physics, have already been excluded.
