Frontier Airlines raises charges for hand luggage
Frontier Airlines plans to claim up to $100 from passengers who want to store hand luggage on their flight.
Frontier Airlines intends to charge up to $100 for one piece of hand luggage and $2 for coffee or lemonade, even though the announcement on Wednesday read that passengers were allowed to keep the entire can.
The new fee applies to hand luggage in the luggage compartment above the seat, small bags under the seat are still free.
Frontier stated that it will charge $25 if the fee is paid in advance, and $100 for travelers who only paid at the flight deck.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O'Malley said the $100 fee is aimed at moving travelers to take care of the payment in advance.
“We don’t want to calculate that amount,” she said.
Airlines began charging charges for the first and second pieces of baggage in 2008.
Passengers who tried to circumvent it have therefore packed as much as possible into their hand luggage, resulting in the luggage compartments over the seat frequently being overcrowded.
Fees are a way to move passengers to take less with them on board.
O’Malley said the new fee isn’t really about making money.
These are Frontier’s most loyal customers who would have clearly stated that it is becoming increasingly difficult to find space in the compartment above the seat.
Passengers who purchase your tickets on the airline’s website do not have to pay.
This means that a passenger on Frontier’s flight ladder may be allowed to carry a piece of luggage free of charge, but the next person will have to pay $100 for a comparable piece of luggage.
O’Malley said Frontier’s website and check-in procedures would be changed so that passengers would be informed of the fee before they arrive at the flight deck.
Frontier’s new hand luggage fee only comes into effect in the summer, there is no exact date yet.
Passengers often skimp on baggage allowances and other charges, but airlines like to resort to them.
They argue that the transportation of luggage costs money and passengers should pay for this service if they wish.
Many on Wall Street see the new baggage charges as a sign that airlines are taking enough money to cover the cost of flying after years of losses.
However, so far, most leave their fingers of fees for hand luggage.
Spirit Airlines Inc. demanded first charges for hand luggage three years ago, and later followed Allegiant Air, also a low-cost airliner.
The only other airline with such a fee is Hungarian Wizz Air, said airline consultant Jay Sorensen, who closely monitors the additional fees.
He estimated in a December 2011 report that the Spirit hand luggage charge would make $50 million a year.
Sorensen, who had previously held a leadership position at Midwest Airlines, recently flew with Spirit and was curious about what to expect at the flight deck if passengers were confronted with the company’s unusual toll on hand luggage.
“The boarding process was one of the smoothest I’ve ever experienced in my career in aviation,” he said.
I expected to see tooth decay and hand-held discussions at the flight deck.
“The plane was full,” he explained, “and the boarding was running like lubricated.”
Frontier also follows Spirit with the 2 dollars required for coffee, tea, lemonade or juice.
The company stated that passengers who bought lemonade or juice should keep the whole can and refill coffee for free.
Water is still free.
US Airways had briefly tried to claim money for refreshments in 2008, but rescinded it seven months later after passengers complained and no other major company had relocated.
Frontier’s move to collect charges for hand luggage if passengers do not buy directly from the airline is the latest initiative to steer customers to their own website.
Airlines pay online travel agencies like Orbitz $10 to $25 per ticket sold.
This provides an incentive for all airlines to move passengers for direct purchase with them rather than through an online travel agency.
Frontier, however, has gone the farthest in this area.
In September, the company started granting half as many airline miles when booking via an online travel agency.
On Wednesday, the miles were once again reduced to 25 percent of the flight route.
A flight booked with a third-party carrier with Frontier over 1000 miles therefore only brings customers 250 miles.
Passengers can also reserve seats exclusively for direct purchases on the Frontier website.
Frontier has a loyal customer base at its Denver headquarters, but the business shrinks and the company loses money.
Revenue fell by 9 percent and flight capacity shrunk by just under 13 percent in the first quarter, according to the financial report released on Wednesday by the parent company, Republic Airways Holdings Inc.
Republic has tried to get Frontier’s finances under control as part of the company’s sale.
