What happens to my e-mail on the go?
E-mail is actually an electronic letter.
In the design of the Internet service, was e-mail technically implemented in the same way as in the conventional mail?
In the design of early Internet services, communication was at the forefront.
Therefore, the basic technical protocols did not take care to create a solid foundation for a safe exchange of letters.
Therefore, a conventional email corresponds to an open postcard rather than a sealed letter.
If the user "Anna" sends an email to "Benni", are the computers of the two then connected directly?
Anna’s email program or browser sends the email to the mail server of her service provider in the first step.
For example, if you have a Gmail account, it would be Google.
This mail server sends the content to the provider that Benni uses.
On the route, the mail can run over several other servers on the Internet.
Bennie can then call his provider for the content.
Will traditional emails be read along the way through the web?
Most emails are read multiple times by software robots on the go.
The sender’s provider usually checks whether the mail carries a malicious program as an attachment.
A virus check is also performed on the receiver systems.
In addition, the providers check whether it is a annoying and unwanted spam email that is deleted immediately or sorted away into a spam folder at least.
Do the robots have another task?
For systems like GMail, the robot also determines the information Google needs to place contextual advertising.
When Anna and Benni communicate via GMail about their upcoming holiday trip, Google may display relevant holiday offers links.
Do unfamiliar people also read the emails?
The likelihood that unauthorized people will be reading an email is extremely low.
Theoretically, this is possible.
In companies, administrators often have the opportunity to read e-mail.
The law enforcement agencies and intelligence services also have legal means of intercepting or taking note of emails.
In addition, there may be illegal expulsion actions.
Is it possible to protect emails from co-reading?
By encrypting according to the OpenPGP standard, an email can be effectively encrypted against co-reading.
With high technical effort, it is also possible to hide the metadata of an e-mail communication, so that it is not even possible to recognize without further ado who has communicated with whom.
