An interesting point is lost in the constant repetition of this ancient story.
Why should an independent Scotland be expected to dance in line with the European Pipeline?
Why exchange the London yoke for that of Brussels, especially now?
This is the real European news: the great post-war plan for the unification of Europe has collapsed.
With the Euro crisis, the project Europe has officially died.
Everywhere in the EU, parties are gaining ground that is hostile to the EU or wants to throw the euro overboard as a community currency.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party – founded only this year – was able to garner almost five million votes in the September Bundestag election and thus effectively expel the Free Democrats (the equivalent of the British Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been domestic resistance to the plan to create a federalist Europe.
However, the current economic crisis turns out to be a turning point.
Due to the stringent austerity policy imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, coupled with the coercive jacket in which the respective national economy is forced by holding on to the common currency, many people believe that the Europe project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments causing excessive budget deficits – that was the case only in Greece.
Instead, the Eurosystem has fixed its members on exchange rates that are advantageous for German exporters – and German politicians would like to do so.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the local currency, southern Europe is again with a built-in productivity disadvantage compared to Germany.
The only way is to cut wages and public spending – driven by Berlin.
Behind the current budgetary and monetary problems lies a deeper European productivity problem.
As a result of the “green” energy directives, which were laid down in Brussels – a code for subsidising French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers – the European industry is paying twice as much for electricity and four times more for gas than the United States.
This is a debilitating cost disadvantage, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
All of the world’s wage fixations do not protect the European petrochemical industry from being pushed into the corner by cheap American shale gas.
The result is a revolt, especially in France, the former EU cheerleader.
After the war, the political elite of France saw the EU as a vehicle with which to keep Germany in check and to lift Paris up with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimacy, and Europe has imposed its own economic policy, with which the affected French economy has to struggle.
The result: Marine Le Pen’s right-wing, EU-enemy Front National has just won a decisive by-election and so the ruling Socialists have placed third.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the vote – a timely warning to the British Labour Party that it cannot assume a split in the right spectrum would automatically mean benefits for the left.
What does Le Pen do with its newly gained popularity among the white French of the working class?
She wants to use the EU elections next year to forge an anti-EU, anti-Community currency block in the European Parliament.
If the anti-EU parties do well in these elections – and that is very well possible – then for the first time such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament.
This is the point I want to go further: in the not too distant future, the growing resentment against the EU and the common currency will come together for the abolition of the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will become more like the “Europe of (sovereign) nations” that General de Gaulle favored.
Germany and some of its satellite economies may hold on to the euro, but France and southern Europe will return to their own currencies.
I expect the UK to distance itself from this project in the hope of meddling with the US.
Washington’s growing interest in the Pacific, however, suggests that Britain will stand alone in the Atlantic rain.
Where does Scotland stay with all of this?
We can choose to be a region of (lastly) small England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests – which includes saying Berlin and Brussels what they can hide behind.
I suspect that Scotland could do very well in a looser European Union if we keep our own currency.
Cooperation with other similarly thinking countries is easier in a non-federated Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider doing the same with Norway and maintaining our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is – remarkably – the most successful political movement against austerity policy in Europe and has won a spectacular majority in 2011 due to the rejection of the proposed (and made) cuts that Labour Finance Minister Alistair Darling and the subsequent Dery-Li responded to.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to opt for independence now, only to get a policy of austerity imposed on Berlin and Brussels.
