“We are very hopeful that this type of vaccination strategy can once again help millions of smokers who have tried to quit and have tried all the methods available on the market, but had to experience that their nicotine addiction is stronger than these approaches,” Cornell said.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been modified to contain the genetic information for the production of nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then produce a constant stream of antibodies.
The antibodies hunt the nicotine molecules in the blood and neutralize them before they reach the brain, making a smoker not experiencing a nicotine high.
In experiments, vaccinated mice who were given nicotine maintained their normal level of activity.
Mice without vaccination, on the other hand, would have taken a “time off,” the researchers explained, a sign that the nicotine had reached their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Former tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
Vaccines had to be given so often to maintain antibody levels that they were expensive and impractical.
However, the cost of the new vaccine is likely to be significantly lower, as it transforms liver cells into antibody factories.
As Professor Crystal said, a future vaccine for humans could, if it is absolutely certain, be given to children before they were tempted to try a cigarette and thus prevent nicotine addiction.
