The U.S. Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) allows U.S. airlines to change their specifications so that passengers can read e-books, watch videos, or play videos on their devices during critical flight phases when they are in flight mode.
During most of the flight, passengers are already allowed to do this, but many people find it annoying that they are not allowed to read their e-books at the start and landing.
Australian airlines observe the decision that U.S. airlines will have to do a lot of work to implement, but do not pursue direct plans to change their regulations.
The aviation safety authority CASA also stated that the announcement would be considered, but stressed that the restrictions on the use of electronic devices in critical flight phases in Australia continue to apply.
“The CASA currently has no specific regulations regarding the use of electronic devices in the aircraft,” it said.
The subject matter is subject to provisions that require airlines to maintain safety at all times and passengers to follow the safety instructions given by cabin crew.
Virgin has already conducted talks with CASA about expanding the use of its Wi-Fi entertainment system on flights and has declared that one is open to change, but these need to be initiated by the legislature.
“We would welcome a review of CASA’s approval of electronic devices, because we are convinced that this would improve the customer experience after we now offer (wireless entertainment) during the flight,” a spokesperson said.
Qantas said they will remain with the current regulations until further notice.
“Our current policies provide that electronic devices are not to be used when starting and landing, and we currently have no plans to change that,” the company said.
The FAA regulations apply to U.S. airlines.
However, we are always interested in developments in regulations that passengers can benefit from, and we will certainly look closely at the FAA decision and the reasons behind it.
The decision affects U.S. companies differently depending on the age of the fleet.
They need to prove that their aircraft can tolerate radio interference from mobile devices, and change manuals, training materials, hand luggage programs, and customer instruction.
“After an airline has confirmed the tolerance of its fleet, it can allow passengers to use portable, lighter electronic devices such as tablets, e-book readers and smartphones at any height,” the FAA said in a statement.
In rare cases of poor vision, the crew will instruct the passengers to turn off the devices during landing.
The group also recommended storing heavier devices safely under the seat or in the compartments above the seats when starting and landing.
