“My husband and I just bought a house, there’s all my money in it,” says Amirthalinga.
Although she earns 3,000 Singapore dollars each month (about 1,730 euros) as a administrative employee and her husband also works, the monthly family income is not enough, she explains.
In fact, demand in parts of Southeast Asia – where household debt is on the rise – is so high that ValueMax, where it made its exchange, became the third real estate listed on the Singapore Stock Exchange this week.
Obtaining jewelry is not only a quick way to get money – $1,300 in the case of Janani Amirthalinga – but also almost as cheap as an unsecured bank loan.
Typically, real estate in Singapore demands an effective annual interest rate of 17 percent, which is just over the 15.4 percent that the United Overseas Bank demands, a local lender with a branch in the same mall.
However, real estate houses offer the advantage that no credit check or proof of income is required here, which is why loans are possible faster than with banks.
That’s why millions of people in the region turn to landlords after families feel the pressure due to rising cost of living and increasing household and consumer debt.
After five years of robust growth since the global financial crisis and cheap loans due to a looser fiscal policy in the developed economies, families with lower and middle incomes are looking for condominiums to make up for the difference in a staggering economy.
This week, the rating agency Standard & Poor's growing domestic debt, mainly due to rising mortgages, described as a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
