Economists are also worried about the high consumer debt in Thailand, which has barely come out of a technical recession this week.
On Thursday, the data showed a continued weakness in exports and a slowdown in consumer demand.
“In the end, this means that, given rising costs, people in the middle to lower segment (the income scale) will try to supplement their income wherever possible,” says Song Seng Wun, an economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Historical peaks in gold prices over the past two years have intensified the trend of buying personal items as people take advantage of the opportunity to turn the family’s jewelry into cash.
In Singapore, about 70 percent of the pledged items in the city’s 200 landlords are gold.
People say to themselves, “The gold price looks good, let’s pledge Grandma’s gold chain and get back next month.”
Thailand’s largest real estate operator, EasyMoney, has seen a 20 percent customer growth in its branches in recent months.
Growth in the real estate business is so strong that ValueMax, operator of the branch in Bendemeer and 15 others in Singapore, wants to expand not only to neighboring Malaysia – where the company operates four houses – but also outside Asia, according to Yea Lee Ching, Managing Director of ValueMax.
The company is funding that with 60 percent of the 66 million Singapore dollars it took up this week with the Singapore Stock Exchange.
