FAA: Passengers can now use electronic devices in airplanes (but not make phone calls)
Air travellers can now use their electronic devices to read, work, play, listen to music and watch movies from departure to landing, but not to make phone calls with their phones, according to the new guidelines released by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in the United States on Thursday.
However, passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately.
How quickly they would be implemented depends on the respective airline, FAA employee Michael Huerta said at a press conference.
The airlines must demonstrate to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated the flight personnel training manuals as well as the rules for storing the equipment in accordance with the new regulations.
The FAA said it had already received plans from some airlines that wanted to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
Among these airlines were Delta and JetBlue.
“Depending on the status of the plan, we could approve the extended use of electronic devices very soon,” the FAA said in a statement.
Passengers are currently required to turn off smartphones, tablets and other devices when the aircraft doors are closed.
They are only allowed to restart when the aircraft has reached a height of three kilometers and gives the captain green light.
Upon entry into the landing flight, passengers must turn them off again and must not start again until the plane has landed.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are insured against electronic disruption could allow their passengers to use the aircraft even when they take off, land, and roll out, the FAA said.
Most new transport aircraft and other aircraft that have been re-equipped for the use of Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, President of the Professional Flight Companion Association, welcomed the changes.
“If the new regulation is implemented safely – and we are working closely with the airline in this regard – both sides will benefit from it,” Glading said.
We are honestly sorry to have to feel like a caretaker on this issue.
However, Internet connections for surfing, exchanging emails, texting or downloading data less than three kilometers remained prohibited, the agency said.
Passengers are asked to put smartphones, tablets and other devices into flight mode.
So there’s still no “Words With Friends,” the Scrabble-like online game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011 when he had to leave an American Airlines jet in public because he refused to turn off the device while the plane was parked on the flight deck.
And heavier devices like laptops still need to be stored, as there is a risk of injury here if they fly through the cabin.
Mobile phone calls during the flight are also banned as well.
The regulatory competence for telephone calls lies with the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), not the FAA.
The FAA may lift ban on certain electronic devices on take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a safety expert on national traffic issues, told CBS News that phones would still be considered a risk.
“Handys are really a problem, not only because they could potentially cause disruption to navigation devices, but because we know from the FCC that transmission from the air can also interfere with transmission masts,” Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to investigate this issue recommended last month that the government allow a wider use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, the pressure on the FAA to loosen restrictions on its use has increased.
Critics such as Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill of Missouri believe there are no valid security reasons for the ban.
The restrictions are also increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of the devices has become ubiquitous.
In some studies, it is said that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore turning off the device.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by air travelers in 1966 after reports of disruptions of navigation and communication devices by passenger-driven FM radios, which at the time represented the latest technology trend, became known.
New aircraft are much more reliant on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed and approved by the FAA so that electronic interference does not matter to them.
Airlines have been offering passengers Wi-Fi for several years when the flight altitude has been reached.
The pilots adapted to Wi-Fi systems are also more insensitive to interference.
The vast majority of passenger aircraft should be suitable for the stronger use of electronic devices according to the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today’s electronic devices generally emit significantly less radio radiation than previous generations.
E-readers, for example, only emit minimal radiation when scrolling.
However, when downloading or sending data, the transmission values are stronger.
Among the advocates of loosening restrictions on the use of devices by passengers is Amazon.com.
In 2011, company employees loaded a passenger plane full of Kindle E-Readers and made a test flight to detect problems, but could not detect them.
Members of the FAA Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about the risk involved in the use of equipment.
Douglas Kidd, of the National Association of Airline Passengers, said he believed the interference with the devices was real, even if the risk was minimal.
Other committee members said that there are only individual reports of pilots arguing for aircraft systems to be disrupted by the devices, and most of them are very old.
However, the Committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to order the deactivation of the devices by passengers when instrument landing under poor visibility conditions.
A grouping from the travel industry welcomed the changes and called them a reasonable adjustment for travelers who would be equipped with technology today.
“We are delighted that the FAA recognizes that a pleasant passenger experience is not at odds with safety,” said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Travel Association.
