Scientists were able to shed more light on the context in which a dog’s tailing is related to its mood.
Previous research had shown that happy dogs with their tail shifted more to the right (from the dog's point of view), while in nervous dogs it was the left side.
But now scientists say that other dogs can perceive these subtle differences and react to them.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trent, said: “It is well known in humans that the left and right halves of the brain react differently to stimuli that cause positive or negative emotions.”
Here we have tried to look at this with other species.
He also noted that in dogs, just as in humans, the right half of the brain is responsible for the movement of the left side and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played different roles in the emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to the lateral tailings of their peers, the researchers monitored the animals while watching these other dogs’ films.
They measured the heart rate of the four legs and analyzed the behavior.
We'll probably soon understand why the tail moves in one, in the other direction.
Professor Vallortigara said: “We showed the dogs movies with dogs – either a true-to-life version or a silhouette to eliminate distracting other aspects, and we were able to control the movement of the tail more to the left or right.”
When the animals saw an otherwise expressive dog moving their tail to the right (as seen from the dog’s wedging perspective), they remained completely relaxed.
But if the tail tends mainly to the left (again from the dog’s point of view), their heart rate rose and they looked restless.
According to Professor Vallortigara, the dogs do not intentionally communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, he is convinced that the dogs would have learned from experience, what movements they should be worried about and when not.
He said: “If you have different encounters with other dogs and you’re more likely to be linked to friendly behavior with your tail and the right side is more likely to produce less friendly behavior, then you’re reacting based on those experiences.”
The researchers say the findings could help dog owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand their pet’s emotions.
John Bradshaw, an expert on dog behavior and guest stipend at the University of Bristol’s Faculty of Veterinary Medicine, said this was not the first study to examine whether left and right are important for dogs.
Last year, a team at the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left when looking at an aggressive dog, and to the right when it comes to a satisfied dog.
In another research paper at the University of Victoria in Canada, the following was stated: “Dogs are more likely to approach a robot dog when his ‘tail’ turns left and not right, rather than getting restless – just unlike in the Italian study.”
According to him, the differences could therefore affect that the dogs in the different studies did not interpret the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs could help, he explained.
“While there is considerable evidence for many different mammals that the two halves of the brain are used for different purposes, many of the details still need to be determined – and dogs are no exception,” Bradshaw said.
But since their behavior is easy to record, it probably won’t be long before we understand why the tail sometimes moves in one direction, sometimes in the other direction.
