Travelling through mud, rivers and jungle for free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle brings free medical help to remote villages in Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend treating hundreds of patients.
There are not many doctors in the West African country, only one for 5,000 people.
Vote here or with your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the top 10 "CNN Heroes of 2013".
You can vote for him or one of the other heroes in the top 10 to choose him as the "CNN Hero of the Year".
The winner will receive $250,000 to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched his sick father repeatedly lose consciousness and travel to hospitals that did not have the means to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon, in 1981.
At first, he only had a broken arm, but then an inflammation was formed that spread to his brain and there caused a hematoma that was supposed to affect him for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” said Georges Bwelle.
We would have brought him out of Cameroon if we had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years accompanying his father to overcrowded clinics and hospitals to get the treatment they had to offer there.
“It’s not easy,” commented Bwelle.
You can leave the house at five in the morning and run to the hospital to be the first, and yet not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some people even die because they have to wait.
The situation has barely changed since Bwell’s father died in 2002.
There is only one doctor for every 5,000 people in Cameroon, according to the World Health Organization.
In contrast, the ratio in the United States is one doctor for 413 people.
But even if there was a doctor for them, most Cameroonians could not afford to visit.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line and nearly three-quarters of health spending in the country is private.
“The only problem they have is poverty,” says Bwelle.
Poverty makes it impossible to enjoy life.
To see his father and so many of his countrymen suffer, Bwelle matured the decision to do something about it.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers conducted 700 free surgeries last year.
He became a doctor himself and worked as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital in Yaoundé.
In addition, he founded a non-profit organization called ASCOVIME, which travels on weekends in rural areas and offers free medical care there.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Nearly every Friday, he and up to 30 people drove into the villages in need of help with the cordoned medical equipment on the roof over unpaved terrain.
Everything does not always go smoothly.
More than once, they had to shove the vehicles through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they will be welcomed like heroes: a feast, singing and dancing and the best accommodation the place has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is really a reason to celebrate and wave – with its wide smile and its limitless energy – is happy to attend the joyous celebration.
The next morning, the team begins to examine hundreds of patients.
“We treat 500 people per ride,” says Bwelle.
They come from a radius of 60 kilometers around the village – and that on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics offers medical care in a number of areas.
Many people are treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others receive crutches, donated glasses or free birth certificates – a document that is required for school, but many poor families simply can’t afford.
In the evening, the team performs simple operations with local anesthesia.
Surgery usually takes place in a school, town hall, or apartment; after surgery, patients stand up and go to the recovery area to make room for the next.
The lighting for the surgery and disinfection equipment is fed by the generator of the group and so Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of Sunday morning.
It’s an exhausting curriculum, but the village musicians usually help keep the team motivated.
“They drum all night so we can stay awake and continue our work,” says Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team returns to the city, tired but proud of the work they have done.
The group – a mix of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students – has performed 700 free surgeries over the past year and knows that it makes a huge difference to the people it helps with its work.
One man explained that the free operation of a rupture he received now allows him to work again.
“This will change the future of my family,” the man said.
In addition to the weekend clinics and his work as a surgeon in the hospital, Bwelle also works at night in private clinics in Yaoundé.
With this second job he finances 60% of his non-profit activity, so Bwelle; the rest comes from private donations.
“I really don’t know when he’s sleeping,” says Katie O’Malley, who studies medicine in her second year at Drexel University in Philadelphia and volunteers in Bwelles Group.
He is always either in the hospital or trying to spend money for the organization so that he can go on these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O’Malley, who come from the U.S. and Europe and support Bwelle, this is an opportunity to gather practical experiences that they would never get at home.
“We can be in surgery where we help shed blood or hold the instruments for Dr. Bwelle,” O’Malley explains.
This would never be possible in America as a medical student in the second year.
Students usually pay for their trip to Cameroon themselves and often bring donated medical supplies.
However, once they are in Yaoundé, Bwelle takes over the accommodation, transportation and guidance.
“He’s definitely a hero,” O’Malley says.
He dedicates his life to this organization and his desire to help the Cameroonian people knows no boundaries.
For Bwelle, the almost constant work is not a burden.
Helping others to live a happier life, and thereby fulfilling a promise he made to his father, brings him great joy.
“I’m so happy when I do this job,” Bwelle says.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do it to bring people back to laughter and to relieve the pain.
