Tourism: Descending to the Romans
At about 120 meters in length, a sewage channel from the Roman period is preserved below Cologne.
Anyone who visits Cologne does not pass the cathedral.
At about 157 meters, the two towers rise to the sky and make it the second tallest church building in Europe.
However, few visitors who admire the two filigree church towers know that there is a lot to discover under the cathedral.
Rainer Schulze is an expert on Cologne Underworld.
The meeting point for its guided tours is the service center of Cologne-Tourism directly at the Cathedral.
The tour starts quite unspectacular: "We start in the underground garage," says Schulze.
In the 1970s, the city fathers wanted a self-righteous city, and so only what wasn’t too big was left of the remnants of the old city walls.
Most users of the car park rush past the Roman remains today and only park their car.
But if you look more closely, you will discover an archaeological site separated by metal grating rods in the park deck D2.
You can see about five-metre-high ruins of hand-teller-sized stones.
“There are remains of the Roman city walls that were built in the second half of the first century AD,” Schulze says.
Before returning to daylight, Schulze lets the participants take a look at a dark, 15-metre-deep hole on the upper level of the park.
This is the well of the old dome, which unfortunately is hardly noticed.
The next station of the tour is the praetorium, and here the participants go down again to the depths.
Here we see the seat of the once most powerful man north of the Alps, the precursor of the CCAA.
What CCAA means, a visitor would like to know.
"The abbreviation stands for "Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium", meaning in good German as much as "City of Roman law and city of Agrippa, founded under Emperor Claudius on the site of the altar for the imperial cult".
And the praetorium is the former state palace, the power center of the Roman Empire on the Rhine.
From the foreground of the exhibition, a tunnel access leads to the Roman sewage canal, which has been preserved here at a length of about 120 meters.
"You can relax a bit along the so-called Cloaca Maxima if you want," Schulze cheers the guests.
Schulze has a surprise.
After getting the key at the box office, he leads the group to a 16-metre-deep, walkable shaft.
“We are now in the Mikwe, a ritual Jewish bath,” he explains.
The Jewish community built their bath deep in the ground to get to the groundwater, which was indispensable for ritual washings.
To this day, at the lower end of the Mikwe, whose origins date back to the eighth century, different water levels can be read through varying levels of the Rhine.
The Mikwe will be part of an archaeological area on the Town Hall Square, for which construction work is due to begin soon.
However, a few more years will pass until completion.
